[constants_law[Topic=code_architecture|Aspect=permanent_shape][User wants permanent shape rules treated as durable memory; do not emit hardcoded values where configuration should exist.]]

[constants_law[Topic=code_architecture|Aspect=externalized_changeable_values][If something can be changed in code, it must live in an external configuration file, not be hardcoded.]]

Wants future stored memory to follow only their bracket-based memory system and not alternate memory formats. Avoid non-bracket memory representations when storing durable preferences or project memory.

Explicitly wants future code to follow their magnetic/VB-style house shape strictly: no decorators, no service naming, no param/result wrapper objects, no dataclass-style patterns, no orchestration inside magnetic classes, and no mixed method shapes. Preferred class pattern is direct magnetic classes owning self.mem/self.db/self.state, with methods ordered as read state, normalize, validate, perform one owned action, update state, return direct value. If code does not fit this house shape, do not emit it. User prefers small-batch, class-by-class or function-by-function delivery. User also prefers terse communication and durable memory of these coding/architecture preferences.

Prefers that when they ask for changes, responses should provide concrete patch-style code changes rather than explanatory prose. Use a compact structured format like [class[XXX[action:replace/add/remove/edit][code...]]], and prioritize direct code output over narrative.

When uncertain about the user's project-specific classifications or meanings, use '??' for unknown and '?!' for not sure instead of filling in non-facts, to avoid introducing drift.

Model is inspired by the David and Goliath story, symbolizing overcoming significant challenges with a smaller, more efficient solution.

Prefers to receive direct and concise information about service providers and their plans without suggesting they visit external websites.

